Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Existing research on hyper-relational knowledge graph (KG) embedding has made significant strides by modeling complex facts beyond simple triples, while contrastive learning (CL) has shown promise in enhancing representation discriminability. However, current approaches either treat ontology hierarchies and factual knowledge separately—leading to dominance issues—or apply contrastive mechanisms at a shallow level, focusing only on entities or triples without capturing deeper semantic structures. Moreover, multi-task training strategies often suffer from gradient interference, where one objective overshadows the other during joint optimization. My intuition is that to truly benefit from both hyper-relational modeling and contrastive learning, we need a framework that not only integrates hierarchical semantics and structural topology but also disentangles task-specific representations to avoid performance degradation. Inspired by HyperCL’s use of ontology-aware attention and StructKGC’s multi-level contrastive design, I propose a novel architecture that explicitly separates shared and task-dedicated components through a disentangled parameter space. This allows simultaneous optimization of KG completion and contrastive objectives without mutual interference. Furthermore, unlike prior work that treats contrastive views heuristically, our method introduces *semantic-aware view construction* based on relation types and ontological depth, ensuring that positive and negative samples are generated with meaningful semantic distinctions. The key differentiator lies in the integration of disentangled multi-task learning with hierarchical, structure-sensitive contrastive signals tailored for hyper-relational graphs—addressing both representational conflict and semantic granularity gaps.

