Both Idea 0 and Idea 1 propose innovative approaches to the joint optimization of hyper-relational KG embedding and contrastive learning, with strong emphasis on mitigating gradient interference and enhancing generalization. However, novelty must be assessed against existing literature.

Idea 0 introduces disentangled towers with orthogonality constraints, semantic-aware positive sampling (SAPS), and hierarchical negative mining. While these mechanisms are well-designed, several components have precedents. The use of disentangled architectures in multi-task KG learning is explored in works like StructKGC and other modular frameworks. Moreover, Paper 3 (HyperCL) already proposes a contrastive learning framework for hyper-relational KGs with hierarchical ontology and concept-aware contrastive loss—this overlaps significantly with SAPS and the concept-weighted loss in Idea 0. Although Idea 0 enhances this with disentanglement and adaptive gating, the core idea of combining contrastive learning with hyper-relational KG completion using ontology-aware design is not sufficiently distinct from HyperCL.

In contrast, Idea 1 ("EvoCL") introduces fundamentally novel concepts: treating multi-task training as an *evolutionary process* with dynamic adaptation via Meta-Gradient Shaping (MGS), Concept Drift-Aware View Generation (CDAVG), and Evolutionary Hierarchical Negative Mining (EHNM). These mechanisms do not appear in any of the provided papers. While Paper 1 (EvolveGCN) evolves GNN parameters over time, it does so for dynamic graphs, not for managing multi-task optimization dynamics. Paper 2 (VMCL) uses variational generation and contrastive learning in inductive settings but lacks evolutionary view selection or gradient shaping. Paper 4 (DCL) uses dual contrastive learning for incremental text classification but operates in NLP with no mechanism for representation drift tracking. None of the papers address *online gradient modulation based on representational stability* or *trajectory-based negative mining*, which are central to EvoCL.

Thus, Idea 1 introduces a paradigm shift—from static multi-task optimization to evolution-aware, self-modulating learning—which is not only novel but opens a new sub-direction in KG representation learning. Its technical components are more differentiated from existing work than those in Idea 0, making it suitable for a top-tier conference contribution.

